Polish patriotic love song created during WW1. "Come back, Johnny, from this war! Back and kiss like years before, I'll give you for this the most beautiful rose!" "Johnny doesn't need anything right now, (....) the white roses has grown on his grave." ♪

Written by Maria Konopnicka in 1908 (music composed by  Feliks Nowowiejski in 1910) as a protest against the German Empire's oppression and suppression of Polish culture. "We won't have Poland's name defamed, we won't step alive into grave!" ♪

Written in 1792 as a farewell to Tadeusz Kościuszko (Polish national hero, famed both for his role in American Revolution and for his leadership of an uprising In Poland) was later sang during November Uprising (1830-1831) with changed lyrics.
